Christopher Brazeau and Bradley Rogers and Harvey Andres and <FRAGMENT_SUPPRESSED> Reine, filed a motion seeking the expungement of the declaration filed on June 13, 2012, in this action, as well as various other relief. For the reasons set out below, the Court will order that the action be suspended for six (6) months, under certain conditions. [2]
The applicants, as listed in the declaration filed on June 13, 2012, are all inmates of the federal penitentiary in Prince Albert, Saskatchewan. They claim damages of more than fifty thousand dollars ($50,000) from the defendant, claiming, according to the description in paragraph 1 of the declaration in question:
 negligence
 the infliction, through negligence, of nervous shocks
 the deliberate infliction of nervous shock
 misconduct in the performance of official duties
 violation of sections 7, 8, 9 and 12 as well as subsection 15(1) of the Charter [3]
They further seek aggravated and punitive damages, attorney-client costs, and various other relief. [4]
The first of the listed plaintiffs, Christopher Brazeau, identifies himself, in paragraph 2 of the statement of claim, as lead plaintiff. None of the applicants hold themselves out as lawyers admitted to practice in any territory or province of Canada. The applicants all signed the declaration. In the documents filed in the Court file, including in the applicant's observations regarding this motion, the applicant Brazeau appears to act as a spokesperson for all of the applicants. [5]
Following the motion to strike initially filed by the defendant, the plaintiffs filed a response, accompanied by a document entitled Amended Declaration, etc.  This document was not filed as a separate document to amend the statement originally filed. This document purports to join two plaintiffs to the action, and to provide additional details beyond what was contained in the initial statement. In the meantime, Justice Snider, on behalf of the Court, issued a reasoned order (reference: 2012 FC 648), in the context of file T-1543-11, another action brought by the same plaintiff, Christopher Brazeau, against the Attorney General of Canada. Judge Snider's order addressed a motion to expunge filed by the Attorney General. [6]
That being so, I have issued a direction requiring the respondent in this case to submit an amended argument regarding Judge Snider's reasons and the changes that purported to have been made to the statement in this case. The defendant has since submitted an amended motion brief. The plaintiffs, through plaintiff Brazeau, responded by filing an amended filing. I will now rule on the request, primarily in light of these documents, but I also intend to take into account the documents previously placed on file. [7]
Remember that none of the plaintiffs are lawyers. In paragraph 6 of their Statement of Case, they specify that they ... have no legal training, and therefore must prepare and defend their case without the assistance or advice of a lawyer ... . It appears, however, from the declaration and other documents filed by the plaintiffs, that one or more of them have devoted considerable time and effort to the study of the questions of law raised in this case. This is one of the problems experienced by litigants who, like plaintiffs, represent themselves in court. Legal training does not, in fact, rely solely on reading documents and researching precedents. Such training also requires in-depth knowledge of law and its practice, as well as a capacity for reflection based on experience and enabling, for example, to know whether an application should be brought before the Court, or before some other authority. It is also a question of knowing precisely where the request fits among the applicable legal principles, and how to formulate it correctly in the necessary documents. Many people know how to use a knife, but that does not make them surgeons. Many people can read procedural rules and legal texts, but not all of them are lawyers. Doing things right requires not just knowledge, but in-depth knowledge applied with the discernment that experience brings. [8]
I do not know whether, for financial or other reasons, the plaintiffs attempted unsuccessfully to retain counsel. I also can't know if they actually had the benefit of legal advice but decided not to follow it. [9]
Here is how, in paragraph 17 of their amended statement of claim, the applicants describe the situation in which they find themselves:
[translation]
17. The inconvenient and harmful positions, and the extreme discomfort that their detention imposes on the applicants, inflict extreme stress and nervous shock on them, in particular because:
a) they are unable to understand, control or compensate for the consequences of what is imposed on them;
b) to cope with the situation, they have to close themselves off, which leads to;
c) an attack on their ability and capacity to desire, experience and express their emotions including the capacity and desire to:
d) express and experience feelings of mutuality, connectedness and meaning;
e) sleep deprivation;
f) an inability to express and/or realize my rights;
g) constantly overwhelmed by despair and a progressive deterioration of self-esteem and self-esteem;
h) loss of control over my ability to tolerate the situation I find myself in and, at the same time, maintain my composure and not go crazy;
i) constant worry and fear about the duration and scope of the effects that all of this will have on my life, on my personality and on my future;
j) the constant and incessant feeling
of a subtle anger born from the fact that I do not have the means to make the fundamental and essential choices of existence
;
k)
all these correspond to the symptoms of morbid depression, antisocial personality disorders, obsessive-compulsive neurosis and post-traumatic stress disorder
;
l)
other disorders which manifested themselves during the defendant's behavior, or which followed it
. [10]
We are faced with the expression of feelings of anger, despair, diminished abilities and loss of control. This reminds us of the words attributed to the Buddha: Clinging to one's anger is like grabbing a burning ember with the intention of throwing it at someone; it's you who gets burned.  In a similar vein, we could cite Greek authors, such as Sophocles and Seneca, who say that those whom the gods want to destroy, they first make mad. [11]
Reading the declaration and the amended declaration, the Court clearly understands that the discontent and frustration that their conditions of detention inspire in the detainees push them to despair and lose their minds. The procedural documents, even as amended, do not allow us to say whether this situation is the normal and expected consequence of their incarceration, or whether it goes beyond what is prescribed by Canadian law. What the declaration contains are observations, whereas it should state:
 the precise circumstances of this case: that is, in relation to the events giving rise to the statement in this case, who did what, when and where;
 the repercussions this had;
 the standard that the law imposes;
 how the circumstances in question violate the standards prescribed by law;
 the resulting harm. [12]
According to the Rules of Court, in particular article 174, every procedural document must contain a concise statement of the material facts. It is not enough, for example, to conclude that one does not have access to the services of a hairdresser, that library services are insufficient or that one is deprived of sunlight. It is appropriate, in fact, to explain clearly and precisely what happened, when it happened and where. What is the standard prescribed by law? To what extent did the defendant's agents fail to meet this standard? All this must be described in an appropriate procedural document. [13]
Should the Court intervene at this time? There are better avenues for expressing such feelings of anger and frustration. There are remedies available to identify and correct deficiencies in services. These include mediation and grievance mechanisms. In their amended case, in paragraph 17, the applicants set out a long list of reference numbers, presumably corresponding to the grievance procedures they have initiated. While the Court has, in some cases, allowed an action despite the existence of a grievance procedure, it is, before bringing a case before the Court, customary and desirable to file a grievance and wait for it to be decided. [14]
Therefore, the Court concludes, with respect to the pleadings, including the draft amended declaration that:
(a) the statement is inadequate because it does not specifically state the precise factual circumstances giving rise to the request; it does not state the applicable standard; it does not explain how and in what way the defendant's agents failed to meet this standard;
(b) the declaration is not, however, so inadequate that authorization to amend it should be refused;
(c) a party cannot be joined to the action simply by filing an amended application; To do this, it is necessary to seek authorization from the Court;
(d) applicants should be represented by a lawyer;
(e) the parties should act calmly and in good faith and, before approaching the Court, exhaust mediation and grievance procedures.
ORDER [15]
CONSEQUENTLY,
this proceeding is suspended for a period of six (6) months so that:
1. the applicants retain the services of an attorney. If they are unable to do so, they must, within five (5) months, bring to the attention of the Court the difficulties they are experiencing and the reasons why they are unable to retain the services of a lawyer;
2. the defendant's lawyer must, within two (2) months, inform the plaintiffs and the Court of the legal services that the plaintiffs could benefit from, including legal aid, the services of a pro bono lawyer or otherwise;
3. before the expiration of this six (6) month period, the parties will inform the Court of the status of the grievance settlement procedures initiated;
4. at the latest at the end of this six (6) month period, the parties will inform the Court of the status of the mediation procedures initiated as well as the efforts undertaken to discuss the disputes between them in order to resolve them;
5. upon receipt of this information, the Court will give directions as to the procedure to be followed in these proceedings;
6. the question of costs will be decided later.
[End of document]
